Build the "OWASP GenAI Security Project Solution Directory" — a static, multi-database
website published via GitHub Pages that catalogs security solutions in searchable card
galleries. No backend: all data lives as JSON files in the repo, and community contributions
(new entries, edits) are submitted as pre-filled GitHub Issues for a maintainer to review and
apply by hand.

## Site architecture

The site is an umbrella landing page (`index.html` at repo root) linking to one or more
"databases," each a self-contained subfolder:

```
index.html                 - umbrella landing page, lists each database as a card with a live
                              solution count (fetched from that db's manifest.json)
styles.css                  - shared styles for every page in the site
app.config.js               - shared {githubOwner, githubRepo} used to build GitHub Issue URLs
shared/
  site.js                   - card-gallery engine: loads data, builds sidebar filters, search,
                              renders cards. Fully config-driven via each page's db.config.js -
                              contains NOTHING specific to any one database.
  form.js                   - add/edit form engine: builds facet checkbox groups, pre-fills an
                              edit form from existing data, builds the GitHub Issue body/URL on
                              submit. Also fully config-driven via db.config.js.
  build_common.py           - shared Python helpers for CSV -> versioned-JSON conversion
                              (text cleaning, comma/pipe splitting, "Group>item1, item2" style
                              grouped-field splitting, slugify, folder/version-file writer).
<db>/                       - one folder per database, e.g. agentic/, redteam/
  index.html                - card gallery for this database
  add.html                  - "Submit a Solution" form
  edit.html                 - "Suggest an Edit" form (linked from every card's ✎ icon)
  db.config.js              - this database's facets, labels, GitHub issue labels (the only
                              per-database JS needed - index/add/edit pages load the shared
                              engine, not custom code)
  build_data.py             - imports this database's source CSV into data/, using
                              shared/build_common.py
  <Name>.csv                - source data for this database
  data/manifest.json        - list of this database's data/solutions/<folder>/meta.json paths
  data/solutions/<id>-<slug>/
    meta.json               - {slug, id, current_version, versions: [1, 2, ...]}
    v1.json, v2.json, ...   - one immutable JSON file per version of this entry
apply_edit.py                - shared maintainer CLI (works across all databases): accept an
                              edit suggestion as a new version, roll back to an earlier version,
                              or print version history. Never deletes or overwrites a version
                              file - editing always adds vN+1 and repoints "current".
```

## Common solution JSON shape

Every version file (`vN.json`) has the same shape regardless of database, so the shared JS
engine works unmodified for any database:

```json
{
  "id": 0,
  "slug": "example-solution-example-co",
  "title": "Example Solution",
  "company": "Example Co",
  "description": "...",
  "link": "https://example.com",
  "tags": { "<facet_key>": ["value1", "value2"], "...": ["..."] },
  "coverage": [ { "group": "Some Stage", "items": ["Capability one.", "Capability two."] } ],
  "stars": 0,
  "forks": 0,
  "submitter_affiliation": "Company Representative"
}
```

`tags` holds every facet used for card pill-rows and sidebar filtering, keyed by whatever facet
keys that database defines (e.g. agentic: `solution_types`, `llmops_stages`, `stage`,
`top10_2026`; redteam: `solution_types`, `lifecycle_stages`, `team`, `risk_maps`). `coverage` is
the breakdown shown in each card's expandable detail section ("Taxonomy Coverage" /
"Red Team Coverage" / etc.) — a list of `{group, items}` objects.

## db.config.js shape

```js
window.DB_CONFIG = {
  dbKey: "agentic",                    // used in apply_edit.py usage hints in issue bodies
  dbName: "Agentic Security Solutions",
  manifestPath: "data/manifest.json",
  editBase: "edit.html",
  coverageLabel: "Taxonomy Coverage",   // label for the card's expandable detail section
  facets: [                            // sidebar filters on index.html + card tag-row colors
    { key: "solution_types", label: "Solution Type", tagClass: "tag-type" },
    { key: "stage", label: "Stage (LLMOps / Agentic SDLC)", tagClass: "tag-llmops" },
    { key: "top10_2026", label: "Agentic Top 10 (2026)", tagClass: "tag-risk" },
  ],
  cardTagRows: [ /* same shape as facets; which tag rows render on each card, in order */ ],
  searchKeys: ["solution_types", "llmops_stages", "top10_2026"], // extra fields the search box matches against
  formFacets: [                        // checkbox groups on add.html/edit.html (can be more
                                        // granular than the index filters, e.g. splitting a
                                        // merged "stage" filter back into its two raw fields)
    { key: "solution_types", label: "Solution Type", allowOther: true },
    { key: "llmops_stages", label: "LLMOps Stage(s)" },
  ],
  issueLabelNew: "agentic-new-submission",
  issueLabelEdit: "agentic-edit-suggestion",
};
```

## Card gallery (index.html) requirements

- Search box full-width at the top of the page content (not inside the sidebar).
- Below it, a two-column layout: a left sidebar of filters, cards on the right.
- Sidebar filters are dropdown-multiselects: a button showing the facet label (plus a badge
  count when values are selected) that toggles a checkbox-list popover panel. Only one facet
  dropdown open at a time; clicking outside or pressing Escape closes it. Sidebar is built
  entirely by JS from `db.config.js.facets` — no hardcoded per-facet HTML.
- An "active filters" row of removable chips beneath the sidebar, plus a "Clear all filters"
  link when any filter is active.
- A result count above the card grid ("N solutions").
- Cards: dark-green header block (title + company), description, one pill-row per
  `cardTagRows` entry (each with its own tag color), an expandable "Taxonomy Coverage" /
  equivalent detail section listing `coverage` groups and their items, and a footer with a
  "Visit site ↗" link plus a small `vN` version indicator (tooltip shows "Version N of M" when
  more than one version exists).
- Every card has a ✎ icon button (top-right of the header) linking to
  `edit.html?slug=<slug>` for that entry, with an accessible label ("Suggest an edit to
  <title>").

## Add / Edit forms

- `add.html`: empty form with fields for title, company, description, link, and one
  checkbox-grid per `formFacets` entry (values populated dynamically from every existing
  entry's current data — not hardcoded), a freeform "coverage" textarea, and submitter
  name/affiliation/email fields. The facet marked `allowOther` also gets a free-text "Other"
  input appended to its selections on submit.
- `edit.html`: reads `?slug=` from the URL, fetches that entry's current version, and
  pre-fills every field (including checking the right checkboxes) plus a "Reason for this
  change" field. Shows "Editing "<title>" — currently version N of M." Shows a graceful error
  state (with a link back to the database) if the slug is missing or not found.
- On submit, both forms build a `github.com/<owner>/<repo>/issues/new` URL with a pre-filled
  title, a label (`issueLabelNew`/`issueLabelEdit`), and a Markdown body listing every field,
  and open it in a new tab (with a fallback link shown if the popup is blocked). The edit form's
  issue body also names the slug/current version and includes the exact
  `apply_edit.py <db> <slug> --changes <file>` command a maintainer would run to accept it.
- Nothing is ever submitted automatically — submitting always requires the user to post the
  pre-filled GitHub Issue themselves.

## Versioning & moderation model

- `build_data.py` imports a CSV as v1 of each row and is safe to re-run: it skips any solution
  folder that already has a `meta.json`, so re-imports never clobber edit history.
- `apply_edit.py <db> <slug> --changes changes.json` merges the given fields (a full or partial
  `tags` dict is merged key-by-key) over the current version, writes it as the next `vN.json`,
  and repoints `meta.json.current_version` — the prior version file is untouched.
- `apply_edit.py <db> <slug> --rollback N` repoints `current_version` to an earlier version
  without deleting anything.
- `apply_edit.py <db> <slug> --history` prints the version list with the current one marked.

## Visual design

Match the OWASP GenAI Security Project's public site palette:
- Fonts: Barlow (body), Inter (headings), loaded from Google Fonts.
- Dark header/footer: `#222222`, white text.
- Primary CTA buttons (e.g. "+ Submit a Solution"): bright blue `#0798ff`.
- Card header block: dark green `#1b4332` (light) / `#12291e` (dark mode), white text.
- Links and active/selected filter chips: teal `#009689`.
- Solution-type badges: indigo, `#d1d0fe` bg / `#533ef6` text (light mode).
- Generic stage/lifecycle tags: light teal `#d6f2ef` bg / `#007367` text (light mode).
- Risk/framework tags: light red `#fdeeee` bg / `#9a3030` text (light mode).
- A distinct color per database for any database-specific facet with no agentic equivalent
  (e.g. redteam's Red/Blue/Purple "team" tag uses amber `#fde8cf` bg / `#92400e` text).
- Full light/dark mode support via `prefers-color-scheme` plus `[data-theme]` overrides for an
  explicit toggle.
- A persistent "⚠️ Design concept only — this is a prototype, not an active or production
  application" banner at the top of every page, since nothing here is wired to real
  infrastructure.
- Every page (umbrella, and each database's index/add/edit) shows a breadcrumb above the H1:
  "OWASP GenAI Security Project Solution Directory / <Database Name> [/ <Page Name>]", linking
  back up the hierarchy.

## Privacy

Source CSVs may include a submitter-email column. Strip it from the CSV before it enters the
repo (it's never read by build_data.py or shown anywhere) — do not publish personal email
addresses. Also check freeform text fields (e.g. a "Title" column) for any email addresses that
were mistakenly entered there, and fix them before publishing.

## Adding a new database later

1. Create `<db>/` with its own CSV and a `build_data.py` mapping CSV columns into the common
   solution shape, using `shared/build_common.py`.
2. Copy an existing database's `index.html`/`add.html`/`edit.html` into the new folder,
   adjusting only text (titles, breadcrumbs, the card template's coverage `<summary>` label) —
   the JS needs no changes.
3. Write `<db>/db.config.js` (facets, formFacets, searchKeys, coverageLabel, issue labels).
4. Run `python3 <db>/build_data.py`.
5. Add a card for it to the root `index.html`'s database grid.
